111Kg 1:1 When David had grown very old, they covered him with blankets, but he could not keep warm, 
111Kg 1:2 so his servants suggested to him, "Let's look for a young virgin woman to take care of you, your majesty. She will be of use to you if you have her lie down near you so that your majesty may keep warm." 
111Kg 1:3 So they conducted a search throughout the territory of Israel for a beautiful young woman, and Abishag the Shunnamite was located and brought to the king. 
111Kg 1:4 The young woman was absolutely beautiful. She served the king and was very useful to him. The king was not sexually involved with her.
111Kg 1:5 Meanwhile, about this time Haggith's son Adonijah began to seek a reputation for himself and decided, "I'm going to be king!" So he prepared chariots, cavalry, and 50 soldiers to serve as a security detail to guard him. 
111Kg 1:6 His father had never challenged him at any time during his life by asking him, "Why are you acting like this?" Adonijah was very handsome and had been born after Absalom. 
111Kg 1:7 He had the support of Zeruiah's son Joab and of Abiathar the priest, who followed Adonijah and assisted him, 
111Kg 1:8 but Zadok the priest, Jehoiada's son Benaiah, Nathan the prophet, Shimei, Rei, and David's personal elite forces would have nothing to do with Adonijah.
111Kg 1:9 Adonijah sacrificed sheep, oxen, and fatted cattle by the Serpent Stone near Enrogel, inviting all of his relatives, the king's sons, and all of the men of Judah who worked for the king, 
111Kg 1:10 but he did not invite Nathan the prophet, Benaiah, David's personal elite forces, or his brother Solomon.
111Kg 1:11 "Haven't you heard?" Nathan asked Solomon's mother Bathsheba. "Haggith's son Adonijah has become king and David, our true king, isn't aware of it?
111Kg 1:12 If you listen to me, you'll save your life and the life of your son Solomon. 
111Kg 1:13 Go right now to King David and ask him, 'Your majesty, you promised your servant that "Your son Solomon will certainly become king after me and shall sit on my throne," didn't you?So why has Adonijah become king?' 
111Kg 1:14 Then, while you are still talking to the king, I'll come in after you and verify your statement."
111Kg 1:15 So Bathsheba went to the king in his private room. Now the king was very old, and Abishag the Shunnamite was attending to him. 
111Kg 1:16 Bathsheba knelt and bowed down to the king, and the king asked her, "What do you wish?"
111Kg 1:17 "Your majesty," she replied, "you promised your servant in the name of the Lord your God, 'Your son Solomon will certainly become king after me and shall sit on my throne.' 
111Kg 1:18 Now look, Adonijah has become king, and your majesty is not aware of it. 
111Kg 1:19 Adonijah has sacrificed myriads of oxen, fattened cattle, and sheep, and he has invited all of the king's sons, Abiathar the priest, and Joab the commander of the army, but he has not invited your servant Solomon. 
111Kg 1:20 And as for you, your majesty, everyone in Israel is looking to you to tell them who will sit on your majesty's throne after you. 
111Kg 1:21 Otherwise, as soon as your majesty is laid to rest with his ancestors, my son Solomon and I will be branded as traitors."
111Kg 1:22 While she was still talking to the king, Nathan the prophet arrived. 
111Kg 1:23 They informed the king, "Nathan the prophet is here." When he had been ushered into the presence of the king, Nathan bowed low in front of the king with his face to the ground 
111Kg 1:24 and asked, "Your majesty, didn't you say 'Adonijah shall be king after me and shall sit on my throne'?
111Kg 1:25 Well now, he went down today and sacrificed lots of oxen, fattened cattle, and sheep, and has invited all the king's sons, the army commanders, and Abiathar the priest. They're having a party together and saying, 'Long live King Adonijah!' 
111Kg 1:26 Of course, he never invited me, Zadok the priest, Jehoiada's son Benaiah, nor your servant Solomon. 
111Kg 1:27 Were you behind this, your majesty, without letting your servants know who would sit on your majesty's throne after him?"
111Kg 1:28 "Call Bathsheba for me," King David replied. So she came in and stood in front of the king. 
111Kg 1:29 "As the Lord lives," the king said with an oath, "who has redeemed me from all sorts of troubles, 
111Kg 1:30 I certainly did tell you in the name of the Lord God of Israel, 'Your son Solomon shall be king after me and shall sit on my throne in my place.' I'm certainly going to make this happen today!"
111Kg 1:31 "King David," Bathsheba said as she bowed low in front of the king with her face to the ground, "your majesty, may you live forever."
111Kg 1:32 "Get me Zadok the priest," King David said, "along with Nathan the prophet, and Jehoiada's son Benaiah." So they were ushered into the king's presence 
111Kg 1:33 and David addressed them. "Take your lord's servants, have my son Solomon ride on my own mule, and take him down to Gihon. 
111Kg 1:34 Have Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet anoint him there as king over Israel. Then sound a trumpet and declare 'Long live King Solomon!' 
111Kg 1:35 After this, you are to follow him back here, and he is to come and sit on my throne and take my place as king, because I've appointed him to be commander-in-chief over Israel and Judah."
111Kg 1:36 "Amen!" replied Jehoiada's son Benaiah to the king. "May the Lord God of your majesty make this happen! 
111Kg 1:37 As the Lord has been with your majesty the king, so may he be with Solomon. May he make his throne greater than the throne of your majesty, King David."
111Kg 1:38 So Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, Jehoiada's son Benaiah, the Cherethites, and the Pelethites went out and had Solomon ride the king's mule all the way to Gihon. 
111Kg 1:39 Zadok the priest brought from his tent a horn filled with oil and anointed Solomon, a trumpet was sounded, and everybody yelled out, "Long live King Solomon!" 
111Kg 1:40 All the people followed after him, playing on wind pipes and so full of joy that the earth shook because of all the noise!
111Kg 1:41 Right about then, Adonijah and all of his guests were just finishing their meal when they heard all the noise. "Why is the city in such an uproar?" Joab asked as he heard the trumpet sounds.
111Kg 1:42 While he was still asking that question, Jonathan, the son of Abiathar the priest arrived, so Adonijah told him, "Come on in, since you're a worthy man and are bringing us good news!"
111Kg 1:43 "No," Jonathan answered. "Our lord King David has installed Solomon as king. 
111Kg 1:44 The king has sent Zadok the priest, Nathan the prophet, Jehoiada's son Benaiah, the Cherethites, and the Pelethites along with Solomon, who is riding the king's personal mule. 
111Kg 1:45 Zadok the priest and Nathan the prophet have anointed him in Gihon, and they just left from there rejoicing, and that's why the city is all in an uproar. That's the noise that you've been hearing! Solomon now sits on the royal throne. 
111Kg 1:47 In addition to all of this, the king's servants have come along to congratulate our lord King David. They've been telling David 'May your God make Solomon's reputation even more famous than yours, and may he make his throne greater than yours!' The king has himself bowed in worship on his own bed 
111Kg 1:48 and said 'Blessed be the Lord God of Israel, who has provided someone to sit on my throne today. I've seen it with my own eyes!'"1
111Kg 1:49 Terrified, all of Adonijah's guests jumped up and ran away. 50Afraid of Solomon, Adonijah also jumped up and headed straight for the horns of the altar.49
111Kg 1:51 "Hey look!" somebody informed Solomon. "Adonijah is terrified of King Solomon! He's gone out, grabbed hold of the horns of the altar, and now he's begging King Solomon, 'Swear to me that you won't put your servant to death with a sword!'"1
111Kg 1:52 "If he's done nothing wrong, not a hair of his head will be harmed," Solomon replied. "But if we find evil in him, he's a dead man."
111Kg 1:53 So King Solomon sent for him, and he was brought down from the altar. When he had arrived, he fell on his face in front of King Solomon, so Solomon told him, "Go home!" 
111Kg 2:1 As David's time to die approached, he addressed his son Solomon with these words:
111Kg 2:2 "I'm headed down the road that everyone who lives on earth travels, so be strong and demonstrate that you're a grown man 
111Kg 2:3 by keeping the charge that the Lord your God entrusted to you. Live life his way, keep his statutes, his commands, his ordinances, and his testimonies, just as they're written down in the Law of Moses, so that you may succeed in everything you do and wherever you go, 
111Kg 2:4 and so that the Lord may fulfill his promise that he spoke about me when he said, 'If your sons pay attention to how they live by walking truthfully in my presence with all their heart and with all their soul, you will never lack a man on the throne of Israel.'
111Kg 2:5 "Furthermore, you're aware of what Zeruiah's son Joab did to me and to those two commanders of the armies of Israel, Ner's son Abner and Jether's son Amasa, whom he killed, and how he shed the blood of wartime during times of peace, staining the very belt he wears around his waist and the sandals he wears on his feet. 
111Kg 2:6 So act consistently with your wisdom, and don't let him die as a peaceful old man. 
111Kg 2:7 Be gracious to the descendants of Barzilla the Gileadite, and provide for them in your household, because they helped me when I had to run from your brother Absalom.
111Kg 2:8 "Pay attention now! You have with you Gera's son Shimei the Benjaminite from Bahurim. He cursed me violently that day when I had to leave for Mahanaim. When he visited me at the Jordan River, I made an oath to the Lord and told him, 'I won't execute you with a sword.' 
111Kg 2:9 But don't let him off unpunished, since you're a wise man and you'll know what you need to do to him. Find a way that he dies in his old age by shedding his blood."
111Kg 2:10 After this, David died, as had his ancestors, and he was buried in the city of David. David had reigned over Israel for 40 years. He reigned in Hebron for seven years and in Jerusalem for 33 years. 
111Kg 2:12 Solomon then assumed his father David's throne, and his kingdom was firmly established.
111Kg 2:13 Later, Haggith's son Adonijah approached Solomon's mother. "Are you here on a peaceful mission?" she asked. "Yes," he replied. 
111Kg 2:14 "I have something to ask you about." "Talk," she told him.
111Kg 2:15 So he replied, "You know that the kingdom should have come to me, and that everyone in Israel intended to place me as the next king. However, the kingdom has turned around and now belongs to my brother, because it went to him from the Lord. 
111Kg 2:16 So now I'm asking one thing from you. Don't refuse me." "Talk," she told him.
111Kg 2:17 Then he asked her, "Please talk to King Solomon for me, since he won't refuse you. Ask him to give me Abishag the Shunnamite as a wife."
111Kg 2:18 "Okay," Bathsheba replied. "I'll talk to the king for you." 
111Kg 2:19 So Bathsheba went to talk to King Solomon for Adonijah. The king rose to meet her, bowed to her, and sat down on his throne. He ordered a throne be set in place for his mother. She sat on a throne to his right 
111Kg 2:20 and said to him, "I would like to make a minor request of you. Please don't refuse me." "What is your request, mother?" the king asked her. "I won't turn you down."
111Kg 2:21 So she asked him, "Give Abishag the Shunnamite to your brother Adonijah as a wife."
111Kg 2:22 But King Solomon replied to his mother, "Why are you asking Abishag the Shunnamite for Adonijah?Why not ask me to give up the kingdom for him, since he's my older brother, and why not ask for Abiathar the priest, and for Zeruiah's son Joab?"
111Kg 2:23 Then King Solomon took this oath in the name of the Lord£º "May God do so to me, and more besides, if Adonijah hasn't endangered his life by bringing up this subject. 
111Kg 2:24 Now therefore, as the Lord lives, who has established me and set me on the throne of my father David, and who has established a dynasty, just like he promised, Adonijah will surely be executed today." 
111Kg 2:25 So King Solomon sent for Jehoiada's son Benaiah, who attacked and killed Adonijah.24
111Kg 2:26 The king also told Abiathar the priest, "Go home to Anathoth. You deserve to die, but I won't kill you today, because you carried the ark of the Lord God before my father David and because you shared all the troubles that my father went through." 
111Kg 2:27 So Solomon fired Abiathar as the Lord's priest, thus fulfilling the promise that the Lord had spoken in Shiloh concerning Eli's household.
111Kg 2:28 When Joab learned what had happened, he ran to the Lord's tabernacle and grabbed hold of the horns of the altar, since Joab had supported Adonijah (though he had not supported Absalom). 
111Kg 2:29 Somebody informed King Solomon, "Joab just ran to the Lord's tabernacle and now he's standing beside the altar!" But Solomon ordered Jehoiada's son Benaiah, "Go kill him!"
111Kg 2:30 So Benaiah went into the Lord's tabernacle and told Joab, "The king orders you to come out!" "No," Joab said, "I'd rather die here!" So Benaiah went and informed the king, "This is how Joab answered me."
111Kg 2:31 The king replied to him, "Do just what he asked. Kill him and bury him so that you may remove from me and from my father's household the guilt that Joab shed needlessly. 
111Kg 2:32 The Lord will repay him for his bloodshed because, without my father David's consent he attacked and murdered two men more righteous and better than he, Ner's son Abner, the commander of Israel's army and Jether's son Amasa, commander of Judah's army. 
111Kg 2:33 May their blood be repaid to Joab and to his descendants forever, and may there be peace shown from the Lord forever to David, to his descendants, to his household, and to his throne."
111Kg 2:34 Jehoiada's son Benaiah then approached Joab, attacked him, killed him, and had him buried at Joab's home in the wilderness. 
111Kg 2:35 The king appointed Jehoiada's son Benaiah in charge of the army to replace Joab and also appointed Zadok the priest to replace Abiathar.
111Kg 2:36 The king sent for Shimei and told him, "Build yourself a house in Jerusalem and live there, but don't go anywhere from there. 
111Kg 2:37 If you ever leave and cross the Kidron Brook, you can be sure that you'll die. You'll be responsible for your own death."2
111Kg 2:38 Shimei replied to the king, "What your majesty has decreed is acceptable to me. I'll do what you've said." So Shimei lived in Jerusalem for quite some time. 
111Kg 2:39 But three years later, two of Shimei's servants escaped to Maacah's son Achish, the king of Gath. Somebody told Shimei, "Look! Your servants went to Gath!" 
111Kg 2:40 So Shimei got up, saddled a donkey, and traveled to Gath to find his servants. He found them and brought them back from Gath.
111Kg 2:41 Later, Solomon found out that Shimei had left Jerusalem, gone to Gath, and had returned, 
111Kg 2:42 so the king sent for Shimei and asked him, "Didn't I make a promise to the Lord and warn you, 'The day you leave and go anywhere else, you can be sure you'll die'?And you said to me, 'What your majesty has decreed is acceptable to me.' 
111Kg 2:43 So why haven't you kept the oath you made to the Lord, and why didn't you obey my personal order to you?"
111Kg 2:44 The king also reminded Shimei, "You know all the evil things that you admit you did to my father David. Therefore the Lord is going to repay you for all of your evil. 
111Kg 2:45 But King Solomon will be blessed, and David's throne will be established in the presence of the Lord forever." 
111Kg 2:46 So the king gave orders to Jehoiada's son Benaiah to go out, attack Shimei, and kill him. That is how the kingdom was established under Solomon's control.
111Kg 3:1 Later, Solomon intermarried with the family of Pharaoh, the king of Egypt by taking his daughter and bringing her to the city of David to live until he had completed building his own palace, the Lord's temple, and the wall around Jerusalem. 
111Kg 3:2 The people were sacrificing at various high places because the temple had not yet been built and dedicated to the Lord.
111Kg 3:3 Solomon loved the Lord, and lived according to the statutes that his father David obeyed, except that he sacrificed and burned offerings at the high places. 
111Kg 3:4 The king used to go to Gibeon to sacrifice, since there was a famous high place there, where Solomon once offered 1,000 burnt offerings on that altar. 
111Kg 3:5 The Lord appeared to Solomon one night in a dream and told him, "Ask me for whatever you want and I'll give it to you."
111Kg 3:6 So Solomon said£º "You have demonstrated abundant gracious love to your servant David, my father, as he lived in your presence truthfully, righteously, and uprightly in his heart. In addition, you have kept on showing this abundant gracious love by giving him a son to sit on his throne today. 
111Kg 3:7 Now, Lord my God, you have set me as king to replace my father David, but I'm still young. I don't have any leadership skills. 
111Kg 3:8 Your servant lives in the midst of your people that you have chosen, a great people that is too numerous to be counted. 
111Kg 3:9 So give your servant an understanding mind to govern your people, so I can discern between good and evil. Otherwise, how shall I be able to govern this great people of yours?"8
111Kg 3:10 The Lord was pleased that Solomon had asked for this, 
111Kg 3:11 so God said to him£º "Because you asked for this, and you didn't ask for a long life for yourself, and you didn't ask for the lives of your enemies, but instead you've asked for discernment so you can understand how to govern, 
111Kg 3:12 look how I'm going to do precisely what you asked. I'm giving you a wise and discerning mind, so that there will have been no one like you before you and no one will arise after you like you. 
111Kg 3:13 I'm also giving you what you haven't requested£º both riches and honor, so that no other king will be comparable to you during your lifetime. 
111Kg 3:14 If you will live life my way, keeping my statutes and my commands, just like your father David did, I'll also increase the length of your life."
111Kg 3:15 Then Solomon woke up and realized that he had dreamed a dream. Then he went back to Jerusalem, stood before the ark of the Lord's covenant, offered burnt offerings and peace offerings, and threw a party for all of his servants.
111Kg 3:16 Right about then, two prostitutes approached the king and requested an audience with him. 
111Kg 3:17 One woman said, "Your majesty, this woman and I live in the same house. I gave birth to a child while she was in the house. 
111Kg 3:18 Three days later, this woman also gave birth. We lived alone there. There was nobody else with us in the house. It was just the two of us. 
111Kg 3:19 This woman's son died overnight because she laid on top of him. 
111Kg 3:20 She got up in the middle of the night, took my son from me while your servant was asleep, and laid him to her breast after laying her dead son next to me. 
111Kg 3:21 The next morning, I got up to nurse my son, and he was dead. But when I examined him carefully in the light of day, he turned out not to be my son whom I had borne!"3
111Kg 3:22 "Not so," claimed the other woman. "The living child is my son, and the dead one is yours." But the first woman said, "Not so! The dead child is your son and the living one is my son." This is what they testified before the king.
111Kg 3:23 The king said, "One of them claims, 'This living son is mine, and your son is the dead one' and the other claims 'No. Your son is the dead one and my son is the living one.' 
111Kg 3:24 "Somebody get me a sword." So they brought a sword to the king. 
111Kg 3:25 "Divide the living child in two!" he ordered. "Give half to the one and half to the other."
111Kg 3:26 The woman whose child was still alive cried out to the king, because her heart yearned for her son. "Oh no, your majesty!" she said. "Give her the living child. Please don't kill him." But the other woman said, "Cut him in half! That way, he'll belong to neither one of us."
111Kg 3:27 The king announced his decision£º "Give the living child to the first woman. Don't kill him. She is his mother." 
111Kg 3:28 When this decision that the king had handed down was announced, everybody in Israel was amazed at the king, because they all saw that God's wisdom was in him, enabling him to administer justice.
