111Kg 4:20 Judah and Israel became as numerous as the sand on the seashore. They enjoyed abundance, and ate, drank, and rejoiced regularly. 
111Kg 4:21 Solomon ruled over all the kingdoms from the Euphrates River to the territory of the Philistines and south to the border of Egypt. They brought tribute and served Solomon throughout his lifetime. 
111Kg 4:22 Solomon's daily provisions were 30 kors of fine flour, 60 kors of meal, 
111Kg 4:23 ten fattened oxen, 20 pasture-fed cattle, 100 sheep, as well as deer, gazelles, roebucks, and domestic poultry. 
111Kg 4:24 He ruled over everything west of the Euphrates River from Tiphsah to Gaza, over all of the kings west of the Euphrates River, and he enjoyed peace on all sides around him.21
111Kg 4:25 Judah and Israel lived safely, and everyone enjoyed their own vine and fig tree from Dan to Beersheba through all of Solomon's life. 
111Kg 4:26 Solomon owned 40,000 stalls for the horses that drove his chariots, and he employed 12,000 men to drive them. 
111Kg 4:27 His officers supplied provisions for King Solomon and for everyone who visited King Solomon's palace, each in their respective month of service responsibility. Nothing ever ran out. 
111Kg 4:28 They also provided barley and straw for the horses and camels to their respective locations, each consistent with their responsibilities.424
111Kg 4:29 God gave Solomon wisdom and great discernment. His insights were as numerous as sand on the seashore. 
111Kg 4:30 Solomon was wiser than any of the eastern leaders and wiser than anyone in Egypt. 
111Kg 4:31 He was wiser than anyone of his day - wiser than Ethan the Ezrahite, Heman, and wiser than Mahol's sons Calcol and Darda. His reputation was known throughout the surrounding nations. 
111Kg 4:32 Solomon wrote 3,000 proverbs and 1,005 songs. 
111Kg 4:33 He described trees - everything from cedars that grow in Lebanon to hyssop that grows on a garden wall. He described animals, birds, reptiles, and fish. 
111Kg 4:34 People came from everywhere to hear Solomon's advice. Every king on the earth heard of his wisdom.
111Kg 5:1 King Hiram of Tyre sent his servants to Solomon when he learned that Solomon had been anointed king to replace his father, because Hiram had been David's lifelong friend. 
111Kg 5:2 Solomon sent this message to Hiram:
111Kg 5:3 "You know that my father David was unable to build a temple dedicated to the Lord his God because he was busy fighting wars all around him until the Lord defeated his enemies. 
111Kg 5:4 But now the Lord has given me rest all around, since I have neither foreign adversaries nor domestic crises. 
111Kg 5:5 So now I'm planning to build a temple dedicated to the Lord my God, just as the Lord told my father when he said, 'Your son, whom I will set on your throne to replace you, will build the temple dedicated to me.' 
111Kg 5:6 Now therefore please order that cedars of Lebanon be cut for me. My servants will work with your servants, and I will pay your servants whatever wages you set, because you know there is no one among us who knows how to cut timber like the Sidonians do."
111Kg 5:7 As soon as Hiram received the message from Solomon, he became so ecstatic that he exclaimed, "Blessed be the Lord today, who has given David a wise son to rule this great people!" Then he sent this message to Solomon:
111Kg 5:8 "I have read the letter that you sent me. I'll do what you've asked about the cedar and cypress timber. 
111Kg 5:9 My servants will transport them from Lebanon to the sea, where we'll make them into rafts and float them by sea to the port that you tell me to send them. We'll have them prepared for transport there and then you can carry them from there. You can meet my needs by providing provisions for my household."
111Kg 5:10 That's how Hiram came to provide Solomon as much cedar and cypress timber as he needed. 
111Kg 5:11 In return, Solomon paid Hiram 20,000 kors of wheat as food for his household, and 20 kors of beaten oil. Solomon provided this amount every year during the construction.
111Kg 5:12 The Lord continued giving Solomon wisdom, just as he had promised, and Hiram and Solomon entered into a peace treaty between themselves.
111Kg 5:13 King Solomon conscripted laborers from throughout Israel. The work force numbered 30,000 men. 
111Kg 5:14 He sent 10,000 men to Lebanon in shifts lasting one month. They worked one month in Lebanon for every two months they worked at home. Adoniram was placed in charge of the conscripted labor. 
111Kg 5:15 Solomon also employed 70,000 heavy-lift workers and 80,000 stonecutters in the hill country. 
111Kg 5:16 Solomon also employed 3,300 officials to supervise the work and to manage the people employed in the construction. 
111Kg 5:17 The king specified that large, expensive stones be quarried so the foundation of the temple could be laid with cut stones. 
111Kg 5:18 As a result, Solomon's builders worked with Hiram's builders, accompanied by the Gebalites, to quarry the stone and to prepare the timber and other stone for the temple's construction.
111Kg 6:1 During the month of Ziv, which was the second month of the fourth year of Solomon's reign over Israel, 480 years after the Israelites left the land of Egypt, Solomon began to build the Lord's temple. 
111Kg 6:2 The temple for the Lord that Solomon was building was 90 feet long and 30 feet wide. 
111Kg 6:3 A portico extended in front of the temple for 30 feet outward, corresponding to the width of the temple. Along the front of the temple its depth was 15 feet. 
111Kg 6:4 Solomon also constructed windows in the temple with specially designed frames.3
111Kg 6:5 Against the wall of the temple he built a series of rooms that encompassed the exterior of the temple walls around the inner sanctuary. He built these side chambers all around the building. 
111Kg 6:6 The lower structures were seven and a half feet wide, the middle structures were nine feet wide, and the third structures were ten and a half feet wide. Offsets were placed all around the temple so that beams would not protrude through the walls of the temple. 
111Kg 6:7 The temple was constructed of stone precut at the quarry so that no hammer, axe, or any other iron implement would be heard in the temple while it was being built. 
111Kg 6:8 A passageway to the side chamber was constructed on the south side of the temple by which people could ascend winding stairs to the middle story, then from there to the third story. 
111Kg 6:9 After Solomon built the temple and finished it, he covered the temple with beams and planks made of cedar. 
111Kg 6:10 He constructed this structure to adjoin the entire temple, seven and a half feet high, and fastened it to the temple with cedar timbers.
111Kg 6:11 Then this message from the Lord came to Solomon£º 
111Kg 6:12 "Concerning this temple that you're building, if you live your life according to my statutes, carry out my ordinances, and keep all of my commands, and live according to them, then I will do what I promised to your father David. 
111Kg 6:13 I will reside among the Israelites and will never abandon my people Israel."
111Kg 6:14 So Solomon kept on building the temple and finished it. 
111Kg 6:15 Then he built the inside walls of the temple, lining them from floor to ceiling with cedar boards, and overlaying the temple floor with boards made of cypress wood. 
111Kg 6:16 He lined 30 feet of the rear part of the temple from floor to ceiling with cedar boards specially constructed for the inside to serve as the most holy place. 
111Kg 6:17 The rest of the main nave in the front was 60 feet long. 
111Kg 6:18 Cedar carvings in the form of gourds and blooming flowers covered the entire interior of the temple so that no stone could be seen.
111Kg 6:19 Solomon also prepared an inner sanctuary within the temple where the Lord's ark of the covenant was placed. 
111Kg 6:20 The inner sanctuary was 30 feet long, 30 feet wide, and 30 feet high, and overlaid with pure gold. The altar was also overlaid with cedar. 
111Kg 6:21 Solomon overlaid the inside of the temple with pure gold, fastened gold chains across the front of the inner sanctuary, and overlaid it with gold. 
111Kg 6:22 He finished the temple by overlaying it entirely with gold, including overlaying with gold the whole altar that was by the inner sanctuary. 
111Kg 6:23 Inside the inner sanctuary Solomon placed two cherubim from olive wood, each fifteen feet high. 
111Kg 6:24 Each wing of one cherub was seven and a half feet long, and each wing of the other cherub was seven and a half feet long, so that the distance from the end of one wing to the end of the other wing was fifteen feet. 
