111Kg 7:8 Solomon's personal dwelling quarters, a separate court behind the hall, was of similar workmanship. Solomon also built a house similar to this for Pharaoh's daughter, whom Solomon had married.
111Kg 7:9 All of these were made with expensive stones, pre-cut according to specifications, hand-sawed inside and out from the foundation to the coping, including from inside to the great court. 
111Kg 7:10 The foundation was made of expensive stone, including large stones fifteen feet long and stones twelve feet long. 
111Kg 7:11 Above these were expensive stones cut according to specifications, and cedar. 
111Kg 7:12 So the great court was surrounded by three rows of cut stone, along with a row of cedar beams, just like the inner court of the Lord's temple and the porch surrounding the temple.10
111Kg 7:13 King Solomon sent for Hiram from Tyre, 
111Kg 7:14 the son of a widow from the tribe of Naphtali, whose father was from Tyre. A bronze worker, he was wise, knowledgeable, and was skilled in all sorts of bronze working. He went to King Solomon and did all of his work.
111Kg 7:15 He fashioned two bronze pillars, each one 27 feet high, with a circumference of 18 feet. 
