111Kg 22:17 So Micaiah replied£º I saw all of Israel scattered on the mountains like sheep without a shepherd. And the Lord told me, 'These have no master, so let them each return to his own home in peace.'"
111Kg 22:18 Then the king of Israel told Jehoshaphat, "Didn't I tell you that he wouldn't prophesy anything good about me, but only evil?"
111Kg 22:19 But Micaiah responded, "Therefore, listen to what the Lord has to say. I saw the Lord, sitting on his throne, and the entire Heavenly Army was standing around him on his right hand and on his left hand.
111Kg 22:20 "The Lord asked, 'Who will tempt King Ahab of Israel to attack Ramoth-gilead, so that he will die there?' And one was saying one thing and one was saying another.
111Kg 22:21 "But then a spirit approached, stood in front of the Lord, and said, 'I will entice him.'
111Kg 22:22 "And the Lord asked him, 'How?' "'I will go,' he announced, 'and I will be a deceiving spirit in the mouth of all of his prophets!' "So the Lord said, 'You're just the one to deceive him. You will be successful. Go and do it.'
111Kg 22:23 "Now therefore, listen! The Lord has placed a lying spirit in the mouth of all of these prophets of yours, because the Lord has determined to bring disaster upon you."
111Kg 22:24 Right then, Chenaanah's son Zedekiah approached Micaiah and struck him on the cheek. Then he asked him, "How did the Spirit of the Lord move from me to speak to you?"
111Kg 22:25 Micaiah replied, "You'll see how when the day comes that you run away to hide yourself in a closet!"
111Kg 22:26 Then the king of Israel ordered, "Take Micaiah and place him in the custody of Amon, the city governor. Hand him over to Joash, the king's son. 
111Kg 22:27 Give him this order£º 'Place him in prison on survival rations of bread and water only until I come back safely.'"
111Kg 22:28 "If you return alive," Micaiah responded, "then the Lord has not spoken by me." Then he added, "Listen, all you people!"
111Kg 22:29 So the king of Israel and King Jehoshaphat of Judah both attacked Ramoth-gilead. 
111Kg 22:30 The king of Israel suggested to Jehoshaphat, "I'll go into battle in disguise, but you keep your royal uniform on." So the king of Israel disguised himself and they both went into the battle.
111Kg 22:31 Meanwhile, the king of Aram had issued these orders to 32 of his chariot commanders£º "Don't attack unimportant soldiers or ranking officers. Go after only the king of Israel."
111Kg 22:32 So when the chariot commanders observed Jehoshaphat, they said by mistake, "It's the king of Israel!" and they turned aside to attack him. But Jehoshaphat cried out. 
111Kg 22:33 When the chariot commanders saw that their target was not the king of Israel, they stopped pursuing him.
111Kg 22:34 Meanwhile, somebody drew his bow aimlessly and struck the king of Israel between the scales where his armor breastplates joined, so he instructed his chariot driver, "Turn around and take me out of the battle, because I've been severely wounded." 
111Kg 22:35 The battle continued on for the rest of the day while the king of Israel was propped up in front of the Arameans until the sun set, at which time he died. The blood from Ahab's wound ran down into the bottom of the chariot.
111Kg 22:36 As the day drew to a close, this order was circulated throughout the army telling the soldiers, "Everybody go back to his city and to his own land." 
111Kg 22:37 So the king died and was brought back to Samaria, and they buried the king in Samaria. 
111Kg 22:38 They washed the chariot by the reservoir of Samaria, and the dogs licked up his blood near where the prostitutes went to bathe, in keeping with the message that the Lord had spoken.
111Kg 22:39 Now as to the rest of Ahab's accomplishments, everything that he undertook, the ivory palace he built, and the cities that he built, they are written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel, are they not?
111Kg 22:40 That's how Ahab died, just as his ancestors had, and his son Ahaziah became king in his place.
111Kg 22:41 Asa's son Jehoshaphat became king over Judah during the fourth year of the reign of King Ahab of Israel. 
111Kg 22:42 Jehoshaphat was 35 years old when he became king. He reigned 25 years in Jerusalem. His mother's name was Azubah. She was the daughter of Shilhi. 
111Kg 22:43 He lived like his father Asa and never abandoned that life. He did what the Lord considered to be right. Nevertheless, the high places were not demolished, and the people continued to sacrifice and burn incense on the high places. 
111Kg 22:44 Jehoshaphat also made a peace treaty with the king of Israel.
111Kg 22:45 Now the rest of Jeshoshaphat's accomplishments, the power that he demonstrated, and how he waged war are written in the book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah, are they not?
111Kg 22:46 He also eliminated the male cult prostitutes who still remained from the time of his father Asa.
111Kg 22:47 There was no king reigning in Edom; there was only a stand-in king. 
111Kg 22:48 Jehoshaphat had ocean-going vessels from Tarshish sail to Ophir for gold, but they never made it because they were shipwrecked at Ezion-geber. 
111Kg 22:49 Ahab's son Ahaziah had offered to go. "Let my servants go with your servants in the ships!" he said. But Jehoshaphat was not willing. 
111Kg 22:50 Later, Jehoshaphat died, as did his ancestors, and he was buried alongside his ancestors in the city of David. Jehoram his son became king in his place.
111Kg 22:51 Ahab's son Ahaziah became king over Israel in Samaria in the seventeenth year of King Jehoshaphat of Judah. He reigned for two years over Israel. 
111Kg 22:52 He practiced what the Lord considered to be evil by living life like his father and mother did. He lived like Nebat's son Jeroboam, who led Israel into sin. 
111Kg 22:53 He served Baal, worshipped him, and provoked the Lord God of Israel to anger, in accordance with everything his father had done.
